<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-255-050  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 255 050.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 15 1989 v6 n19 p64(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>System aids drug delay. (Business applications digest: healthcare)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   DataBeam Corp. (products).andO;Product:   Databeam CT1000 (Teleconferencing equipment) (usage).andO;Topic:     Document DeliveryApplications.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>In large multinational drug companies, part of the delay in introducing drugsstems from the time required to travel between sites or to mail documentsfrom one location to another, according to Joseph Lombardino, director ofdevelopment planning at pharmaceutical firm Pfizer Inc.'s headquarters inGroton, Conn.andM;Now document conferencing, which allows people in separate locations to view,point at and modify a document simultaneously, may cut drug development time.andM;Pfizer installed DataBeam CT1000 document-conferencing systems in Groton andat a laboratory in Sandwich, England.andP;  The system is built around anAT-compatible PC running DataBeam Corp. software.andP;  It includes scanners fordocument entry, high-resolution monitors and a combination laser printer/faxmachine.andM;One standard telephone line exchanges documents and pointer information,while another handles voice communications.andP;  When a document is displayed inone location, users can point at particular portion of it; the document andthe pointer will be duplicated on the distant screen.andM;Document conferencing, says Edward Wiseman, Pfizer's executive director ofresearch administration, ''fosters debate, enabling scientists and cliniciansnot only to walk their distant counterparts through a document line by line,but also to explain the relevance of that data.''andM;DataBeam Corp. can be reached in Lexington, Ky., at (606) 273-3204.andO;</TEXT></DOC>